After that, the disk-space issue should be resolved without needing the aggressive prune -a. Then proceed with the rebuild from docs/phase-d-rollout.md.

The 500 from /adapterDefinition is the same root cause as before — /tmp filling up again, because:

Each failed mp-build/mp-test attempt leaves another zombie swagger_server container
The cleanup_all() in build-pak.sh only runs when build-pak.sh itself runs — mp-test --port 8181 invoked directly bypasses it
So your mp-test sessions have been adding zombies that build-pak.sh then has to chew through, but if there were many before the script's first cleanup, /tmp may already be exhausted
Single decisive command to break the cycle:


# 1. Kill ALL azure/microsoft/swagger containers (running or stopped)
sudo docker ps -a --format '{{.ID}} {{.Image}} {{.Command}}' \
  | grep -iE 'azure|microsoft|swagger' \
  | awk '{print $1}' \
  | xargs -r sudo docker rm -f

# 2. Clean /tmp leftovers (mktemp dirs from crashed builds)
sudo rm -rf /tmp/pak-inspect /tmp/test_def.py
sudo find /tmp -maxdepth 1 -type d -name 'tmp*' -exec rm -rf {} + 2>/dev/null

# 3. Reclaim Docker storage
sudo docker container prune -f
sudo docker image prune -f

# 4. Hard reset: restart docker daemon to clear any stuck port bindings or socket state
sudo systemctl restart docker
sleep 3

# 5. Confirm all clean
sudo docker ps -a
df -h /tmp /var/lib/docker
sudo ss -tlnp 2>/dev/null | grep ':8181' || echo "8181 free"

# 6. Retry the build — should now print "Reaping..." (zero) and "dynamic native loader: 19 kinds substituted"
cd /opt/aria/Aria-MP-Builder
bash scripts/build-pak.sh 2>&1 | tee debug/build.log
grep -E 'Reaping|native loader|substitut|adapterDefinition' debug/build.log
Step 4 (docker daemon restart) is the part we haven't tried yet — it nukes any stuck port bindings, leftover networks, or daemon-side state we can't see. After that, the slate is fully clean.

